# Report: Herbert Hoover’s Response to the Demands of the Bonus Army

## Introduction

The Bonus Army was a significant and controversial episode in American history during the Great Depression. It involved thousands of World War I veterans who marched on Washington, D.C., in 1932, demanding early payment of bonuses promised for their military service. President Herbert Hoover’s response to this movement has been widely analyzed and critiqued. This report provides a detailed, comprehensive, and objective examination of Hoover’s actions and policies regarding the Bonus Army, drawing on multiple reliable sources to present facts, figures, and interpretations.

---

## Background: The Bonus Army and Its Demands

Following World War I, the U.S. government promised veterans a monetary bonus for their service, which was formalized in 1924 through legislation. The bonus was issued in the form of certificates, which veterans could redeem for cash starting in 1945. However, the onset of the Great Depression in 1929 caused widespread unemployment and economic hardship, particularly for veterans. By 1932, approximately 12,000 to 15,000 veterans, along with their families, converged on Washington, D.C., forming what became known as the Bonus Army. Their demand was for immediate cash payment of their bonuses, including interest, to alleviate their financial distress ([Becca7828, 2017](https://brainly.com/question/3105833)).

---

## Hoover’s Initial Position on the Bonus Payments

President Hoover opposed the early payment of the bonuses. He believed that paying the bonuses ahead of schedule would require raising taxes or increasing government debt, which he feared would worsen the already fragile economy. Hoover’s administration argued that Congress had already legislated the payment schedule, and altering it would disrupt fiscal policy. When a bill proposing early payment was introduced in Congress, it was rejected by the Senate, reflecting Hoover’s stance and the broader political opposition ([Isabell Schimmel, 2018](https://www.enotes.com/homework-help/how-did-herbert-hoover-respond-to-the-demands-of-the-bonus-army-2069160)).

---

## The Bonus Army’s Encampment and Rising Tensions

The veterans set up makeshift camps in Washington, D.C., including a large one at Anacostia Flats. Their presence became a growing concern for local authorities and the federal government. On July 28, 1932, the Attorney General ordered the veterans to vacate government property. The Washington police attempted to enforce this order but faced resistance from the veterans, leading to violent clashes and the deaths of two veterans ([Becca7828, 2017](https://brainly.com/question/3105833)).

---

## Hoover’s Decision to Use Military Force

Following the failure of local law enforcement to disperse the Bonus Army, President Hoover authorized the use of the U.S. Army to remove the veterans forcibly. General Douglas MacArthur, along with Major Dwight D. Eisenhower and Major George S. Patton, led the military operation. The troops used tear gas, cavalry, tanks, and infantry to clear the veterans’ camps. The operation resulted in injuries and at least one death among the protesters. The military also destroyed the veterans’ makeshift shelters ([agrippa, 2017](https://brainly.com/question/3105833); [Wiki User, 2013](https://brainly.com/question/3105833)).

---

## Impact and Public Perception

The violent eviction of the Bonus Army was widely criticized and became a significant political liability for Hoover. Many Americans viewed the use of military force against impoverished veterans as harsh and insensitive. The incident contributed to Hoover’s loss in the 1932 presidential election to Franklin D. Roosevelt. Roosevelt, in contrast, welcomed a subsequent Bonus Army march in 1933 and sought more compassionate solutions to veterans’ issues ([agrippa, 2017](https://brainly.com/question/3105833)).

